reviews.review_text:
Good Job This one sounds real good. 
 On other versions of this show someone comments the freak dancing on Phil's side . I clearly recall that like it was yesterday. 
 Back to recording everyone comes threw on this copy.

Good aud of a good show There has been improvement in the available sound quality of 1986 shows, a year with historically limited choices for aud sources.  This is one example though it’s always tough to get a good recording or auditory experience first-hand for that matter, in a shed.  Add the early enforcement of the taping section that made stealth taping in front of board more difficult and you have a tougher year for auds.  This is a good one though I did switch to the sbd, admittedly for the second set.  That didn’t exist as an option back in the day either.

This is a weird show, a short burst of weirdness and then they’re gone in the blink of an eye.   Early Ramble on Rose is precursor to the opener it would become for a day down the road in Washington.  The Row Jimmy is a rare respite from the rock n’ roll briskness during this tour.  Quickly our heads are snapped back with the kooky combo of BIODTL>Touch and it’s a (just) pre-coma Touch so it’s almost as fast as its pair.  They get intense quickly in Playin’ in the Band and just before they let you complacently drift away, Jerry starts a textbook Uncle John’s that’s over way too soon as the band appears to be giving Alpine the bum’s rush into Drums.  Jerry seems to sense this and switches to the “China Doll” setting on his pickup but the move quickly gets picked up by Bobby and the drummers into an abstract jam that floats along for a while until the pre-drums is stretched to a more respectable 21 minutes.  

Space is very spacey and goes into the China Doll Jerry was thwarted from singing earlier.  The Playin’ Reprise resumes the intense spaciness of that version right away, goes afterward into a pleasant GDTRFB and an unexpected Lovelight that goes places most Lovelights don’t go.  A fluid Bobby vocal drives this loose, jazzy version that, like the jam before Drums seems to want to kick it up a notch to make up for a short show.  The double encore possibly has the same motivation but who knows and who cares?
